11:37.934 --> 11:51.858
And their resolve, these brave Iranian believers remind me of the three Hebrew young men, Hanania, Michelle, and Azariah in the book of Daniel, better known by their Babylonian names, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego.

11:52.738 --> 12:03.135
You see, the Babylonian king Nebuchadnezzar had erected a massive golden image of himself and commanded everybody to worship it or face death in a fiery furnace.

12:04.017 --> 12:14.795
The three Hebrews famously defied his order by saying, Our God whom we serve is able to deliver us from the burning fiery furnace and he will deliver us out of your handle king.

12:15.957 --> 12:18.962
But if he does not, we want you to know

12:19.234 --> 12:24.220
that we will not serve your foreign gods or worship the image of gold that you have set up.

12:25.401 --> 12:29.485
The king was enraged and ordered the furnace heated seven times hotter.

12:30.587 --> 12:35.973
The three Hebrews were thrown into the furnace, but the intense heat killed the executioners, not them.

12:37.555 --> 12:45.243
Astonished, king Nebuchadnezzar actually saw four men, not three, walking unbound and unharmed in the fire.

12:45.784 --> 12:47.826
And the king said the fourth man looked like

12:48.098 --> 12:49.199
a son of the gods.

12:49.780 --> 12:58.891
That's widely interpreted by Bible scholars as either the angel of the Lord or a Christophany, a pre-incarnate appearance of Jesus.

12:58.912 --> 13:05.119
The Hebrews emerged completely unscathed, no burns, no singed hair, not even the smell of smoke on their clothing.

13:05.640 --> 13:10.486
That was a great miracle, and indeed our God is able to deliver any of us at any time.

13:11.267 --> 13:16.914
But God sometimes ordains his servants to become martyrs to receive a greater reward.

13:17.538 --> 13:26.211
in the New Testament, the book of Hebrews, addresses suffering not as an accident or a lack of faith but as a necessary part of our life of faith.

13:27.053 --> 13:31.159
Suffering and hardships from time to time are intended to mature us.

13:32.121 --> 13:46.002
Hebrews chapter 11 is famously referred to as the Hall of Faith because it lists various biblical heroes of faith who suffered many hardships including extreme brutality like being stoned, being

13:46.082 --> 13:53.473
destitute living in caves and even being sawn into as church history records happened to the prophet Isaiah.

13:54.675 --> 13:58.201
All of this to demonstrate that suffering is compatible with deep faith.

13:59.002 --> 14:09.979
These heroes are celebrated because they accepted joyfully the seizure of their property and refused release from torture, knowing that they had a better and lasting possession in heaven.

14:10.880 --> 14:14.546
The text states that the world was not worthy of these believers.

14:15.106 --> 14:20.714
The next chapter Hebrews 12 explains suffering as divine discipline or training.

14:21.616 --> 14:24.420
Similar to how a loving father trains a child.

14:25.081 --> 14:28.185
Suffering can be a sign of sonship or daughtership.

14:29.087 --> 14:34.755
The text argues that enduring hardship is proof of being a legitimate child of God.

14:35.697 --> 14:40.904
You see, if a believer never experiences discipline, we would be considered illegitimate children.

14:41.545 --> 14:42.066
However,

14:42.370 --> 14:46.056
suffering is described as purposeful rather than punishments.

14:46.897 --> 14:55.270
Learning to endure hardships is intended to produce a harvest of righteousness and peace and to allow believers to share in the Lord's holiness.

14:56.291 --> 15:00.999
The Book of Hebrews encourages the faithful to fix her eyes on Jesus as our example.

15:01.900 --> 15:10.994
Jesus endured the ordeal and agony of the cross because he was mindful of the joy of the harvest he would receive as a result of the travail of his soul.

15:11.778 --> 15:26.480
In Hebrews 13, 13, we believers are encouraged to go forth to him outside the camp, bearing his reproach and viewing our hardships when we too are often rejected as a way of identifying with the Lord's own rejection.

15:27.682 --> 15:38.258
Hebrews 13, 3, encourages us to remember those who are mistreated and those in prison like many of our Iranian brothers and sisters right now as if we were with them in chains.

15:39.106 --> 15:51.823
So, Sovereign Lord, we petition you to protect your people and to repeat what you did in Exodus 11-7 in Egypt, how you made a miraculous difference between your people and their enemies.

15:52.324 --> 16:00.996
We bless you that although the regime has cut off internet connections, believers in Iran are never cut off from their connection with you, Lord.

16:02.478 --> 16:05.522
So, dear friends, I want to tell you about one of my heroes in the faith,

16:06.178 --> 16:11.487
Henry Martin is why the regarded as the most famous missionary in the history of Persia, modern day Iran.

16:12.369 --> 16:16.696
His short life was only 31 years after he was born in 1781.

16:16.897 --> 16:21.064
Yet he made a lasting impact on Persia and the world.

16:22.126 --> 16:26.293
God is surely always able to make something of our lives whether long or short.

16:26.834 --> 16:31.442
Henry Martin was an Anglican priest, scholar and linguist from England

16:32.034 --> 16:45.268
His brief but intense life's work resulted in his groundbreaking translation of the New Testament into the Persian language Farsi, earning him enduring recognition among evangelicals, historians, and mission scholars.

16:46.209 --> 16:57.622
Henry Martin is often called the first proud submissionary to live in Persia, and he's celebrated for his sacrificial devotion despite battling severe illness and all sorts of spiritual warfare.

16:58.583 --> 17:01.426
Martin was a brilliant student at Cambridge University.

17:01.730 --> 17:07.558
He felt a call to missions after reading about William Carey's groundbreaking work in India.

17:08.479 --> 17:12.925
Martin joined the East India Company as a chaplain arriving in India in 1806.

17:14.487 --> 17:25.743
There he translated the New Testament in Psalms into Hindustani and began work on Persian scriptures inspired by his assistant, who was a converted Muslim.

17:25.763 --> 17:31.090
But tuberculosis-like symptoms prompted doctors to recommend a drier climate for Henry Martin.

17:31.746 --> 17:36.852
He arrived in Persia in 1811 to refine and publish his Persian New Testament.

17:37.512 --> 17:44.560
He was the first Protestant missionary to reside in Persia, working amid Muslim scholars, mulas, and officials.

17:45.401 --> 17:51.968
He engaged in deep theological debates with Shia clerics, defending Christianity with humility and scholarship.

17:52.749 --> 17:57.174
He revised his Persian New Testament, making it more accurate and idiomatic.

17:57.834 --> 18:01.298
He also translated portions of the Psalms and other scriptures.

18:01.954 --> 18:08.825
Despite illness and loneliness, he showed remarkable grace, often winning respect, through piety and intellect.

18:09.546 --> 18:14.213
Martin's journals reveal a man consumed with love for Messiah and love for souls.

18:14.874 --> 18:20.923
You could say he performed exploits in translation due to endurance that could have only been supernatural.

18:21.544 --> 18:30.738
Despite advanced tuberculosis, extreme heat, and travel hardships, he completed monumental translation work in just over a year in Persia.

18:31.202 --> 18:39.150
His New Testament became foundational for later Bible work in Persian-speaking regions and influenced generations of Iranian seekers.

18:39.890 --> 18:44.234
Many modern Iranian Christians trace inspiration to his legacy.

18:45.315 --> 18:56.026
Henry Martin's death at age 31 is seen as a seed sewn in hard soil, contributing to the spiritual harvest that's currently happening in Iran's contemporary revival.

18:56.927 --> 19:00.530
The life and letters of Henry Martin have inspired missionaries worldwide

19:00.642 --> 19:04.966
including the great missionary to China, Hudson Taylor, and others.

19:05.667 --> 19:16.598
Henry Martin's story reminds me that true missionary greatness often lies in quiet faithfulness, scholarship, and dying to self, planting seeds that God waters in his own time.

19:17.659 --> 19:25.928
In these latter days, when Iranians are turning to the risen Lord Jesus and unprecedented numbers, we rejoice in the faithful labors of Henry Martin.

19:26.448 --> 19:28.210
His memory is a blessing.

